	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"> Watch out for slowdown when programming an SNES game or scrolling demo.  The SNES has a very slow cpu and it will slowdown very easily if you don't know how to optimize code.<br /><br />To optimize your code, always use less than 4 sprites.  Using more will take to long for the slow cpu to process.  Stick to 16x16 sprites.  32x32 sprites take 4 times as much cpu power to process.<br /><br />Avoid using too many layers of parallax, and hardware effects like transparency and Mode-7.  Transparancy and Mode-7 take a lot of processing work.<br /><br />Also don't try to move backgrounds too fast.  Remember the Snes does not have the blastprocessing feature the Sega Genesis has, so it can't make the backgrounds scroll on autopilot like the Sega Genesis can, so it takes a lot of cpu power to move the background.</div>
<br />
<br />That sounds more like satire than cluelessness.

		

		</td>
